  "notes": "Cheyenne (Tsėhésenėstsestȯtse) — Algonquian language of Montana and Oklahoma. Uses the standard practical orthography developed by Wayne Leman and the Cheyenne translation project: three vowel qualities a e o, each of which may carry high tone (á é ó, low tone unmarked) or be voiceless/whispered (ȧ ė ȯ). Long vowels are written double. ⟨š⟩ = /ʃ/, ⟨'⟩ = glottal stop /ʔ/. ⟨h⟩ is realised as [s]/[ʃ] before certain consonants in the practical spelling, which is designed to guide pronunciation rather than to be strictly phonemic.",
